      "role": "user",
      "content": "Okay, that makes sense. So it's mostly about negligence. \n\nI'm still a bit worried about this part about \"defending\" them too. Does \"defend\" mean if someone else sues the client because of something I did, I actually have to pay for their lawyers and manage the whole legal fight for them? That sounds like it could get really messy and expensive very quickly. Is there a way to limit that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"defend\" part of the indemnification clause can be a bit confusing, but it's not necessarily about defending the client in a lawsuit. Instead, it's about defending the client's rights and interests in the event of a claim or lawsuit.\n\nIn this context, \"defend\" means that you'll take steps to investigate and address any claims or allegations made against the client, and you'll work to resolve the matter in a way that's favorable to the client. This might involve negotiating a settlement, defending the client in a lawsuit, or taking other actions to mitigate the client's losses.\n\nHowever, you're right that this can get messy and expensive. To limit your exposure, you can try to negotiate with the client to include specific language in the agreement that clarifies the scope of your responsibilities. For example, you might ask the client to agree that you'll only be responsible for defending against claims that are related to your own negligence or wrongdoing, and not against claims that are based on the client's own actions or omissions.\n\nAdditionally, you can also try to negotiate a \"limited defense\" provision, which would limit your responsibilities to defending the client against claims that are related to your own performance under the agreement. This can help",
      "source": "target",
